Security Information and Event Management (SIEM)

Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) is the most critical core component a SOC cannot live without. In other words, without a SIEM, there is no SOC. Ironically, SIEM is usually the most expensive tool in the SOC arsenal. The term SIEM is based on two combined terms; Security Information Management (SIM) and Security Event Management (SEM): 

  • Security Information Management (SIM): is a technology that provides long-term log storage, analysis, and reporting capabilities. 
  • Security Event Management (SEM): is a technology that provides event correlation and real-time alerting capabilities for security analysts. 


A SIEM is a software solution that aggregates and analyzes activities from many different sources across your entire infrastructure. It collects log and event data generated by applications, operating systems, network devices, and endpoints and brings it together into a single centralized platform for analysis.

 

Figure - zoom in

As a SOC analyst, SIEM is the tool you will use most during your day-to-day job activities. Think of it as a repository for the entire infrastructure logs, such as firewalls, operating system logs, network authentication logs, AntiVirus logs, EDR logs, etc. In a nutshell, anything that generates logs on your entire network. SIEM is the tool you use to answer questions you encounter during investigations and incident response, such as what happened, when, how, where and by whom. 

On top of that, there are a bunch of other functions a SIEM offers, such as:

  • Events correlation: correlation is the process of contextually analyzing a large number of events to detect threats. 
  • Alerting: alert when a specific action happens. For example, send an email alert to the security team when outbound traffic to a single IP address exceeds the acceptable limit. If a system or two inside your network are uploading Gigs of data to an external IP, this could be a possible data exfiltration attempt. 
  • Ticketing system: a place to keep incident notes and track incidents from the beginning till closure. Including information such as who reported the incident, when, the assigned analyst, incident analysis, and resolution.
  • Automation: group and automate routine, manual analyst actions to increase operational efficiency. For example, if ransomware is discovered on an endpoint, a workflow will kick off to automatically isolate the machine from the rest of the network.


There are many SIEM products in the market, such as IBM QRadar, Exabeam, LogRhythm, Elastic, and Splunk. Free alternatives also exist, such as: 

  • AlienVault OSSIM: OSSIM is an open-source security information and event management system (SIEM) developed in 2003. The project was acquired later by AT&T.
